{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588858"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15183"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15183"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.14,0.14,0.02,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64610"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7874"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50044"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21312"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64610"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESolid cancers demonstrate different patterns of incidence across age groups. Some malignancies predominantly affect young adults, while others are more common in older populations. For reasons that are still not clear, a number of different cancers are being seen with increasing frequency in the younger populations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common solid cancer in men aged 15-35 years?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bladder","Colorectal","Prostate","Stomach","Testicular"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile many solid cancers predominantly affect older adults, \u003Cstrong\u003Etesticular \u003C/strong\u003Ecancer\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis unique in being the most common solid malignancy in young men aged 15-35 years. The peak incidence occurs between ages 20-34 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApart from non-melanoma skin cancers, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostate \u003C/strong\u003Ecancer is the most common cancer in Australia. This cancer, together with \u003Cstrong\u003Ebladder\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Estomach \u003C/strong\u003Ecancer, typically affect older populations, with median age at diagnosis being over 60 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColorectal\u003C/strong\u003E cancer is one of the five commonest cancers in Australia, the others being breast, prostate, melanoma and lung cancer. Colorectal cancers are being found with increasing frequency in young adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for testicular cancer include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECryptorchidism (undescended testicle)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFamily history\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrior testicular cancer in the contralateral testicle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite ethnicity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Testicular cancer is the most common solid malignancy in men aged 15-35 years","Peak incidence of testicular cancer occurs between ages 20-34 years","Risk factors for testicular cancer include cryptorchidism, family history, and prior contralateral tumour"],"references":["Gaddam SJ, Chesnut GT. Testicular Cancer. 2023 May 27. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 33085306.","Peate I. Men and cancer: the gender dimension. Br J Nurs. 2011 Mar 24-Apr 14;20(6):340, 342-3. doi: 10.12968/bjon.2011.20.6.340. PMID: 21471888.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50044"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15183"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50044"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T11:03:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T11:04:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7874"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64610"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember 